7 An Act relating to labor; creating the Actionable
Response for Industry Skills and Excellence in
8 Oklahoma Task Force (ARISE-OK); describing
legislative intent and purpose; defining terms;
9 providing for Task Force membership; creating
guidelines for Task Force members; creating
10 guidelines for appointed members; providing Task
Force duties; requiring reports; providing report
11 deadlines; providing guidelines for compensation and
reimbursement; requiring staffing and support;
12 establishing sunset date; providing for
noncodification; providing for codification; and
13 providing an effective date.
14
15
16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
18 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
19 A. The Legislature finds that Oklahoma's long-term economic
20 growth, business competitiveness, and workforce capacity depend upon
21 strategic coordination between employers, education providers,
22 workforce systems, and state agencies.
23 B. It is the intent of the Legislature to:
24 1. Identify barriers to workforce entry and participation;
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3128 Page 1

1 2. Strengthen workforce pipelines in key industries;
2 3. Align education and training systems with employer needs;
3 4. Support apprenticeships, technical training, and career
4 development;
5 5. Enhance Oklahoma's economic competitiveness through a
6 modernized, responsive workforce system; and
7 6. Ensure recommendations are industry-driven, data-informed,
8 and actionable.
9 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
10 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 651 of Title 40, unless there is
11 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
12 A. There is hereby created the Actionable Response for Industry
13 Skills and Excellence in Oklahoma Task Force (ARISE-OK).
14 B. The purpose of ARISE-OK is to evaluate statewide workforce
15 readiness, identify barriers to employment, strengthen workforce
16 pipelines, and advance strategies that support business growth and
17 economic competitiveness.
18 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 652 of Title 40, unless there is
20 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 For purposes of this act:
22 1. "Industry representative" means an individual employed by or
23 affiliated with a private-sector business operating within the State
24 of Oklahoma;
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3128 Page 2

1 2. "Registered apprenticeship" means a program registered with
2 the United States Department of Labor or the Oklahoma Office of
3 Workforce Development;
4 3. "Task Force" or "ARISE-OK" means the Actionable Response for
5 Industry Skills and Excellence in Oklahoma Task Force created in
6 Section 2 of this act; and
7 4. "Workforce barriers" includes transportation, childcare,
8 credentialing, reentry, housing, and other obstacles preventing
9 workforce entry or retention.
10 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
11 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 653 of Title 40, unless there is
12 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
13 A. The Actionable Response for Industry Skills and Excellence
14 in Oklahoma Task Force (ARISE-OK) shall consist of the following
15 voting members:
16 1. The Commissioner of Labor, who shall serve as chair, or
17 designee;
18 2. The Executive Director of the Oklahoma Employment Security
19 Commission, or designee;
20 3. The Executive Director of the Oklahoma Department of
21 Commerce, or designee;
22 4. The State Director of Career and Technology Education, or
23 designee;
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3128 Page 3

1 5. The Chancellor of The Oklahoma State System of Higher
2 Education, or designee; and
3 6. The Secretary of Agriculture, or designee.
4 B. The following shall serve as ex officio, nonvoting members:
5 1. The Executive Director of the Oklahoma Workforce Commission
6 (OWC), or designee;
7 2. The Executive Director of the Oklahoma Space Industry
8 Development Authority (OSIDA), or designee;
9 3. The Executive Director of the Oklahoma Center for the
10 Advancement of Science and Technology (OCAST), or designee;
11 4. One representative of the Oklahoma Tribal Finance Consortium
12 (OTFC); and
13 5. The Lieutenant Governor, or designee.
14 C. In addition, the Task Force shall include eleven (11)
15 appointed voting members as follows:
16 1. To be appointed by the Commissioner of Labor:
17 a. an apprenticeship or workforce training specialist,
18 b. a workforce training provider representative, and
19 c. a workforce barrier-reduction specialist;
20 2. To be appointed by the Governor:
21 a. an energy sector representative, and
22 b. a technology sector representative;
23 3. To be appointed by the Speaker of the Oklahoma House of
24 Representatives:
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3128 Page 4

1 a. a construction sector representative,
2 b. a manufacturing sector representative, and
3 c. a veteran or military transition representative; and
4 4. To be appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the Oklahoma
5 State Senate:
6 a. an agriculture sector representative,
7 b. a health care sector representative, and
8 c. a statewide business or industry representative.
9 D. Members shall serve until the Task Force submits its final
10 report, unless replaced by the appointing authority. The appointing
11 authority has discretion to replace a member he or she appointed.
12 E. If any appointed member has not been selected by the
13 designated appointing authority within sixty (60) days of the
14 effective date of this act, the chair of the Task Force shall make
15 the appointment to fill the vacancy. Such appointment shall serve
16 until the appointing authority selects a member or until the Task
17 Force submits its final report, whichever occurs first.
18 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 654 of Title 40, unless there is
20 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 The Actionable Response for Industry Skills and Excellence in
22 Oklahoma Task Force (ARISE-OK) shall:
23 1. Evaluate Oklahoma's workforce readiness and talent shortages
24 across all industry sectors;
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3128 Page 5

1 2. Identify regulatory, statutory, and practical barriers to
2 employment;
3 3. Recommend strategies to strengthen workforce training,
4 apprenticeships, career and technical education, education
5 alignment, and employer participation;
6 4. Study workforce challenges within agriculture,
7 manufacturing, energy, construction, health care, technology, and
8 veteran transition sectors;
9 5. Engage rural, urban, and veteran communities to ensure
10 statewide workforce responsiveness;
11 6. Coordinate studies and data requests within the Oklahoma
12 Workforce Commission to avoid duplication and ensure complementary
13 efforts;
14 7. Provide statutory and administrative recommendations to
15 improve workforce effectiveness and business competitiveness;
16 8. Address workforce challenges not explicitly within the
17 Commission's statutory mission, including cross-sector coordination,
18 long-term strategic workforce policy, and structural barriers; and
19 9. Leverage expertise from ex officio members for emerging
20 industries and workforce insights.
21 SECTION 6. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 655 of Title 40, unless there is
23 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3128 Page 6

1 A. The Actionable Response for Industry Skills and Excellence
2 in Oklahoma Task Force (ARISE-OK) shall submit the following written
3 reports of findings and legislative recommendations, as follows:
4 1. Interim report by December 1, 2027;
5 2. Second report by December 1, 2028; and
6 3. Final report by December 1, 2029.
7 B. Each report shall be submitted to:
8 1. The Governor;
9 2. The President Pro Tempore of the Oklahoma State Senate;
10 3. The Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives;
11 4. The Oklahoma Workforce Commission; and
12 5. The public via an online posting by the Department of Labor.
13 SECTION 7. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
14 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 656 of Title 40, unless there is
15 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
16 A. Members of the Actionable Response for Industry Skills and
17 Excellence in Oklahoma Task Force (ARISE-OK) who are state employees
18 shall receive no additional compensation for duties performed under
19 this act.
20 B. Legislative or appointed members who are not state employees
21 may be reimbursed for necessary travel expenses in accordance with
22 the State Travel Reimbursement Act, subject to available funds.
23 C. No member shall receive a stipend or per diem for service on
24 the Task Force.
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3128 Page 7

1 SECTION 8. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 657 of Title 40, unless there is
3 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 The Department of Labor shall provide staff support, meeting
5 coordination, report posting, and administrative assistance to the
6 Actionable Response for Industry Skills and Excellence in Oklahoma
7 Task Force (ARISE-OK).
8 SECTION 9. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
9 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 658 of Title 40, unless there is
10 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
11 A. The Actionable Response for Industry Skills and Excellence
12 in Oklahoma Task Force (ARISE-OK) shall terminate on December 31,
13 2029, unless continued by an act of the Legislature enacted no later
14 than the 2029 Regular Session.
15 B. Prior to termination, the Task Force shall submit its final
16 report, and the Legislature may extend, modify, or continue the Task
17 Force through subsequent legislation.
18 SECTION 10. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
